---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Nav from '../../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
import MobileTesterPreview from '../../components/MobileTesterPreview.tsx';
import { NEWSLETTERS, formatNewsletterDate } from '../../lib/newsletters';

// DRAFT NEWSLETTER for May 2026 issue.
// This is a hardcoded preview while we iterate on copy.
// Once approved, this content moves to a Contentful `newsletterIssue` entry
// and this file is replaced by the dynamic [slug].astro route.

const meta = NEWSLETTERS.find((n) => n.slug === 'may-2026')!;
const { title, preheader, publishedAt, heroImage } = meta;

// Image placeholders use placehold.co. Swap for real OWR-hosted assets before publish.
const img = (label: string, w = 1200, h = 600) =>
  `https://placehold.co/${w}x${h}/1C1C1C/FFD700/png?text=${encodeURIComponent(label)}`;

const APP_URL = import.meta.env.PUBLIC_APP_URL ?? 'https://oldworldrankings.com';
const tUrl = (region: string, slug: string) => `${APP_URL}/${region.toLowerCase()}/tournaments/${slug}`;
const pUrl = (handle: string) => `${APP_URL}/players/${handle}`;
const linkClass = "text-owr-gold-dark hover:underline";
---

<Layout title={`${title} | Old World Rankings`} description={preheader}>
  <Nav />

  <main class="pt-24 pb-20">
    <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">

      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="mb-10 text-center">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold tracking-widest uppercase text-owr-gold-dark dark:text-owr-gold mb-3">
          OWR Newsletter, May 2026
        </p>
        <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white leading-tight mb-4">
          {title}
        </h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 max-w-2xl mx-auto">
          {preheader}
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-500 mt-6">
          Published {formatNewsletterDate(publishedAt)}
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- Hero image -->
      <figure class="mb-12 -mx-4 sm:mx-0">
        <img
          src={heroImage}
          alt="Skaven army block under a 'We Shall Eat The Warp' banner"
          class="w-full sm:rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800"
        />
      </figure>

      <!-- Body -->
      <div class="newsletter-body text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 text-lg leading-relaxed space-y-5">

        <p>
          A lot has shipped this past few weeks, and a lot has happened <em>around the Old World</em>. <a href={tUrl('us', 'adepticon-2000-pt-warhammer-old-world-championship')} class={linkClass}><strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Adepticon</strong></a> ran 71 players in the US. Spanish qualifiers cracked 75. The <a href={tUrl('uk', 'tow-6-nations-team-event')} class={linkClass}>TOW 6 Nations Team Event</a> packed 54 across the UK. The scene is genuinely massive now.
        </p>

        <p>
          And meanwhile, tournaments hosted directly on OWR (a platform built for the Old World, not retrofitted from somewhere else) are growing fast. The mobile apps just hit closed beta. And <a href="#battle-hub" class={linkClass}>Battle Hub</a> got its first proper rework off the back of a couple of months of real events and player feedback.
        </p>

        <p>Here's what's new, who's playing, and what's coming.</p>

        <!-- 1. Team tournaments -->
        <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white !mt-12 !mb-4">
          Team tournaments, fully supported
        </h2>

        <figure>
          <img src="/images/newsletter/may-2026-team-hero.png" alt="OWR team tournament view on desktop and mobile" class="w-full rounded-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800" />
        </figure>

        <p>
          The single biggest ship this cycle. Team tournaments (pairs, doubles, full team events) are now first-class on OWR. TOs pair the teams, captains pair their own players, and captains can pay entry for the whole team in one go. Team and individual wins, scores, and awards are all tracked seamlessly side by side, so the standings page knows the difference between an individual rank and a team rank without anyone having to wrangle a spreadsheet.
        </p>

        <p>If you've been holding off running a team event because the tooling wasn't there, it is now.</p>

        <!-- 2. Battle Hub redesign -->
        <h2 id="battle-hub" class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white !mt-12 !mb-4 scroll-mt-20">
          Battle Hub, redesigned
        </h2>

        <figure>
          <img src="/images/newsletter/may-2026-battlehub-hero.png" alt="Battle Hub on mobile: match overview, score entry, secondaries, and soft scores" class="w-full rounded-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800" />
          <figcaption class="text-xs text-gray-500 italic mt-2">
            Match overview, score entry, secondary objectives, and soft scores. The whole player flow during a round.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          Battle Hub is the screen players use during a tournament. Find your next pairing, see your table number, log your battle score, confirm your opponent's, watch standings update between rounds, look back at past rounds and matchups. It's the on-the-day app for players.
        </p>

        <p>
          Battle Hub originally shipped just a couple of months ago, and this is its first big iteration based on real-world use at real events. Cleaner typography, better information density, faster jumping between pairings and standings, dedicated flows for captain pairing in team events, and tighter score entry that handles secondaries and soft scores in one pass.
        </p>

        <p>
          The not-so-secret goal here is to keep moving toward what we cheekily call eradicating TOs, i.e. making the platform handle so much of the day-to-day running of an event that TOs can finally play in their own tournaments. Battle Hub doing more for players is a big step toward that.
        </p>

        <!-- 2.5 Secondary scoring -->
        <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white !mt-12 !mb-4">
          Secondary scoring, fully flexible
        </h2>

        <figure>
          <img src="/images/newsletter/may-2026-secondaries-templates.png" alt="Secondary objectives panel with template dropdown showing Special Features, Breaking the Enemy, Baggage Trains, Domination, Strategic Locations, and Custom Objective" class="w-full rounded-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800" />
          <figcaption class="text-xs text-gray-500 italic mt-2">
            Drop in templates from the Matched Play guide, or define your own custom objectives.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          Our goal is full phone-based scoring, turn by turn, with no paperwork at the table. Secondary objectives are a big step toward that. Templates for the official Matched Play scenarios are built in (Special Features, Breaking the Enemy, Baggage Trains, Domination, Strategic Locations, Capture the Standards, all there), and on top of that you can configure fully custom objectives with your own VP or BP values, names, and rules text.
        </p>

        <figure>
          <img src="/images/newsletter/may-2026-secondaries-config.png" alt="Round configuration dialog selecting King of the Hill scenario with Baggage Trains and Special Features secondary objectives" class="w-full rounded-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800" />
          <figcaption class="text-xs text-gray-500 italic mt-2">
            Per-round scenario setup pulls in the right secondaries automatically, but you can adjust before locking the round.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          Assign objectives per scenario or per round, players score them in Battle Hub during the match (no spreadsheet, no scoresheet, no chasing TOs at the end of the day), and standings can rank by secondary BP as a tiebreaker on top of the usual battle points and SoS. The whole pipeline from setup to standings is wired up.
        </p>

        <!-- 3. Run on OWR -->
        <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white !mt-12 !mb-4">
          Real tournaments running on OWR
        </h2>

        <figure>
          <img src="/images/newsletter/may-2026-cold-combat.jpg" alt="Players setting up tables at Old Hammer Cold Combat 2026" class="w-full rounded-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800" />
          <figcaption class="text-xs text-gray-500 italic mt-2">
            The hall at Old Hammer Cold Combat, May 2026. 47 players, three rounds, run fully on OWR.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          Quietly, in the background, TOs have started running their entire events on OWR: registration, payment, pairings, scoring, the lot. It's still early days, but the first proper events have wrapped.
        </p>

        <p>
          The headline: <a href={tUrl('au', 'old-hammer-cold-combat-2026')} class={linkClass}><strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Old Hammer Cold Combat</strong></a> in Australia ran <strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">47 players</strong> over three rounds on 1 May, fully on OWR. That's the biggest OWR-hosted event so far, and it landed inside the global top five tournaments for the past six weeks. Massive credit to the Old Hammer crew for backing the platform on a real event of that size.
        </p>

        <p>Two more for the shoutout list:</p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>
            <span class="mr-1" aria-hidden="true">🇮🇪</span>
            <a href={tUrl('ie', 'exploding-dice-old-world-gt-2026')} class={linkClass}><strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Exploding Dice Old World GT 2026</strong></a>, full 5-round GT format, run on OWR, 17 to 18 April. Proper grand-tournament shape.
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="mr-1" aria-hidden="true">🇨🇳</span>
            <a href={tUrl('cn', 'guangzhou-2-electric-boogaloo')} class={linkClass}><strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Guangzhou 2: Electric Boogaloo</strong></a>, 16 players, 5 rounds. The China scene is one of the quiet success stories.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          The pattern across all three: rounds run on the platform, scoring entered live, standings update automatically, players see their position in real time.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white !mt-10 !mb-3">
          Coming up, hosted on OWR (and increasingly global)
        </h3>

        <p>A spread of upcoming events running fully on the platform, across four countries:</p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>
            <span class="mr-1" aria-hidden="true">🇳🇿</span>
            <a href={tUrl('nz', 'hell-games')} class={linkClass}><strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Hell Games</strong></a> (16 May). 48-player cap, 6 already in.
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="mr-1" aria-hidden="true">🇦🇺</span>
            <a href={tUrl('au', 'winter-in-the-north')} class={linkClass}><strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Winter In The North</strong></a> (22 May).
            <span class="inline-block ml-1 px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wide rounded-full bg-owr-gold text-gray-900">33 of 30 spots filled</span>
            Already over capacity. Demand is real.
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="mr-1" aria-hidden="true">🇮🇪</span>
            <a href={tUrl('ie', 'exploding-dice-old-war-rtt-june-2026')} class={linkClass}><strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Exploding Dice Old War RTT</strong></a> (5 June). Same crew as the April GT, back for an RTT.
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="mr-1" aria-hidden="true">🇦🇺</span>
            <a href={tUrl('au', 'snake-eyes-more-mulchy-more-cakey')} class={linkClass}><strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">SNAKE EYES: More Mulchy More Cakey</strong></a> (5 June). 100-player cap, 30 in already. Probably the biggest OWR-hosted event on the calendar right now.
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="mr-1" aria-hidden="true">🇨🇳</span>
            <a href={tUrl('cn', 'guangzhou-3-march-into-summer')} class={linkClass}><strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Guangzhou 3: March into Summer</strong></a> (10 July). The Guangzhou series keeps rolling.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          If you're a TO and you've been on the fence about running your event on OWR,
          <a href="/docs/create-tournament" class={linkClass}>our tournament hosting docs walk you through everything</a>. It's a lot less than you think.
        </p>

        <!-- 4. Mobile apps in private beta -->
        <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white !mt-12 !mb-4">
          Mobile apps, now in private beta
        </h2>

        <div class="my-8">
          <MobileTesterPreview />
        </div>

        <p>
          The iOS and Android apps are now in closed beta. Pairings, standings, score entry, list submissions, and live tournament updates, all on your phone. The TestFlight and Play Store internal tracks are open and the first wave of testers is in.
        </p>

        <p>
          We're putting them through their paces ahead of the public launch, with an emphasis on team tournaments (newest feature, most surface to verify) and the on-the-day scoring flow. More on this when we open it up wider.
        </p>

        <!-- 5. Shareable player profiles -->
        <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white !mt-12 !mb-4">
          Player profiles look great when you share them
        </h2>

        <figure>
          <img src="https://oldworldrankings.com/opengraph/player/@asb" alt="OWR player profile preview card" class="w-full rounded-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800" />
          <figcaption class="text-xs text-gray-500 italic mt-2">
            Drop a <a href={pUrl('@asb')} class={linkClass}>player profile</a> link in Discord, Bluesky, or Facebook and you'll get a card like this. Try it with your own profile.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          You know the preview cards that pop up when you paste a link into Discord, Bluesky, or Facebook? That little image is generated by something called an Open Graph (OG) image. Until recently we used a third-party service to render ours for OWR player profiles, and they went dark with about as much warning as an Ungor ambush. That kicked off a slightly frantic few hours of building our own.
        </p>

        <p>
          The result is better anyway: every player profile now generates and self-hosts its own preview card on our side, no more upstream surprises. Each card shows the player's name, region, global rank, faction rank if they're top-10 in any faction, and recent achievements with podium derivation.
        </p>

        <p>
          Paste a link to <code class="px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800 text-sm">oldworldrankings.com/players/[your-handle]</code> into Discord, Bluesky, Facebook, or anywhere else, and the unfurl looks proper.
        </p>

        <!-- 6. Sponsorships -->
        <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white !mt-12 !mb-4">
          Sponsorships are open
        </h2>

        <p>
          The platform now has a proper sponsorship system. Stores, accessory makers, dice and mat brands, and event series can book ad placements that rotate across tournament pages, stats pages, and key flows.
        </p>

        <p>
          We hand-pick every sponsor. They have to actually care about the Old World, not just treat it as another scene to advertise into. That filter is the whole point. The first two sponsors are live, and we'd back both of them in our own hobby spending:
        </p>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 my-6">
          <a
            href="https://oldworldrankings.com/sponsor-ads/3261e4a2-1c0e-43ed-814e-947116283ec5/click?scope=regional"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="block group"
          >
            <figure class="flex flex-col items-center bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 group-hover:border-owr-gold/60 dark:group-hover:border-owr-gold/40 transition-colors p-4">
              <img src="/images/sponsors/mighty-melee.png" alt="Mighty Melee Games" class="max-h-32 w-auto" />
              <figcaption class="text-xs text-gray-500 italic mt-3 text-center">Mighty Melee Games</figcaption>
            </figure>
          </a>
          <a
            href="https://oldworldrankings.com/sponsor-ads/801b6b36-7440-407b-b82e-42cd3e6012c2/click?scope=regional"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="block group"
          >
            <figure class="flex flex-col items-center bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 group-hover:border-owr-gold/60 dark:group-hover:border-owr-gold/40 transition-colors p-4">
              <img src="/images/sponsors/ukresinprints.png" alt="UK Resin Prints" class="max-h-32 w-auto" />
              <figcaption class="text-xs text-gray-500 italic mt-3 text-center">UK Resin Prints</figcaption>
            </figure>
          </a>
        </div>

        <p>
          The pitch is simple, and it works both ways. OWR has thousands of Old World players across 22 countries who care deeply about this game. Sponsors get to reach an audience that's genuinely engaged with the hobby, and players get to find the stores, makers, and event organisers that care just as much about the Old World as they do.
        </p>

        <p>
          Interested? <a href="https://www.oldworldrankings.com/sponsor-deck" class={linkClass}>Sponsor deck here</a>.
        </p>

        <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 italic">
          And if you'd rather not see ads at all, <a href={`${APP_URL}/pricing`} class={linkClass}>OWR Pro</a> users browse the entire platform ad-free.
        </p>

        <!-- 7. Quality of life -->
        <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white !mt-12 !mb-4">
          The little things
        </h2>

        <p>
          A grab-bag of quality-of-life improvements that won't get their own headline but make a real difference:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>
            <strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Pay for another player.</strong> Mostly comes up in singles events: a parent paying for their kid, a mate covering someone who can't get to checkout. The same plumbing also lets a captain settle the entry for an entire team in one go, with every team member auto-marked as paid. TOs get a "Copy Payment Link" action on the attendee menu so they can drop a personal payment link into Discord or email when someone's struggling to find the original invite.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Battle Board projector themes.</strong> Two new high-contrast theme variants for the in-hall display, picked from a TO dashboard selector so you don't have to fiddle with the projector mid-event.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Hide my player name.</strong> A new privacy toggle in profile settings if you'd rather not appear in public rankings or leaderboards.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Bulk army list download.</strong> TOs can grab every submitted list as a single PDF from the attendees screen.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <!-- 8. CTA -->
        <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white !mt-12 !mb-4">
          Run your tournament on OWR
        </h2>

        <p>
          The team-tournament work, the Battle Hub redesign, scoring objective templates, Best Painted voting, secondaries scoring. It's all built. <a href={tUrl('au', 'old-hammer-cold-combat-2026')} class={linkClass}>Old Hammer</a> just ran a 47-player event on it. The tools are there.
        </p>

        <p>
          If you've got a tournament coming up, even a small RTT, give it a try. The setup flow walks you through everything, and we're around in Discord if you get stuck.
        </p>

        <p class="text-center !mt-10">
          <a
            href={`${APP_URL}/host`}
            class="inline-block bg-owr-gold text-gray-900 font-semibold px-6 py-3 rounded-lg hover:bg-owr-gold-dark transition"
          >
            Host a tournament &rarr;
          </a>
        </p>

        <!-- OWR Pro thank-you callout -->
        <aside class="!mt-14 p-6 sm:p-8 rounded-xl border border-owr-gold/40 bg-owr-gold/5 dark:bg-owr-gold/10">
          <h3 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-3">
            Built by Pro supporters
          </h3>
          <p class="text-base text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            Team tournaments. The Battle Hub rebuild. Secondary scoring. Mobile beta. The OG image work. The sponsorship system. The handful of quality-of-life wins above. Every single thing in this newsletter got built because <a href={`${APP_URL}/pricing`} class={linkClass}><strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">OWR Pro</strong></a> supporters are funding it.
          </p>
          <p class="text-base text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mt-3">
            Genuine thanks to everyone who jumped on early. You're the reason this is shipping at the pace it is, and the reason we can keep building.
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-4">
            If you've been on the fence, OWR Pro is the lever. Ad-free browsing, the full tournament hosting toolkit, and you're directly fuelling the next batch of work.
          </p>
          <p class="!mt-6">
            <a
              href={`${APP_URL}/pricing`}
              class="inline-block bg-owr-gold text-gray-900 font-semibold px-6 py-3 rounded-lg hover:bg-owr-gold-dark transition"
            >
              Become an OWR Pro supporter &rarr;
            </a>
          </p>
        </aside>

        <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-12 pt-8 border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800">
          Keep rolling dice,<br />
          <strong class="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Gommo &amp; the OWR team</strong>
        </p>

        <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-500 mt-6 text-center">
          <a href="/newsletter" class={linkClass}>Read past issues &rarr;</a>
        </p>

      </div>
    </article>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
